+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Do We Really Need a Security Industry?                             |
|   from the only-if-software-had-no-bugs dept.                      |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Thursday May 03, @16:11 (Security)         |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/03/1936237           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]netbuzz noted that Bruce Schneir's latest column [1] discusses the
security industry where he points out that "The primary reason the IT
security industry exists is because IT products and services aren't
naturally secure. If computers were already secure against viruses, there
wouldn't be any need for antivirus products. If bad network traffic
couldn't be used to attack computers, no one would bother buying a
firewall. If there were no more buffer overflows, no one would have to
buy products to protect against their effects. If the IT products we
purchased were secure out of the box, we wouldn't have to spend billions
every year making them secure."

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/03/1936237

Links:
    0. http://www.networkworld.com/community/?q=buzzblog
    1. http://www.wired.com/politics/security/commentary/securitymatters/2007/05/securitymatters_0503


