| RIAA Backs Down Again in Chicago                                   |
|   from the can't-win-them-all dept.                                |
|   posted by CowboyNeal on Thursday May 03, @18:30 (The Courts)     |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/03/2142246          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]NewYorkCountryLawyer writes "The RIAA seems to have a problem making
things stick in the Windy City. It has once again [1] backed down in BMG
v. Thao, after suing a misidentified defendant. Same thing occurred last
October in [2]Elektra v. Wilke. In the Thao case, the RIAA based its case
on information that the cable modem used to partake in file sharing was
registered to Mr. Thao. However, it turned out that Mr. Thao was [3]not
even a subscriber (pdf) of the [4]ISP (pdf) at the time of the alleged
file-sharing, and therefore did not have possession of the suspect cable
modem at that time."

